The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	 Pune: Bangalore boy Chikkarangappa returned a card of two-over 73 in the final round to comfortably defend his Lalit Suri Western India Junior Golf Championship title at the par-71 Poona Club Golf Course Friday. Chikka finished on top with a total of 12-over 296 to win the tournament by four shots. Khalin Joshi, returned the best card of the day  a round of even-par 71  to finish second.        
	 New Delhi: The Billiards and Snooker Federation of India (BSFI) is all set to hire foreign coaches for its players for the first time. The BSFI has got six applications from different countries and will choose one coach each for pool and snooker disciplines. According to BSFI vice president Ravi Tandon, coaches from Taiwan, Japan, Philippines, Singapore and Dubai have sent their application.         
	 Chennai: Indoor Asian Games gold medallist Aditya Mehta routed Saurav Kothari 7-3 in the final to win the VIP Matrix All-India Invitational Snooker tournament, finishing the year on a high. In the lop-sided final, Aditya beat Kothari 72, 65, 53 and 74 to clinch the title.         
	 New Delhi: A fire broke out late on Thursday at the under construction rugby stadium for next years Commonwealth Games in the Indian capital. According to media reports on Friday that the blaze had started in the venue seats and taken almost two hours to extinguish but no casualties were reported.        
	 Tokyo: Teenager Ryo Ishikawa won the Japan Professional Sports Award for the second year running on Friday. The 18-year-old, who became Japans youngest Order of Merit winner in 2009, accepted the award from Japanese PM Yukio Hatoyama.         
	 Ahmedabad: Former West Indian cricketer Jimmy Adams will be in the city to train a group of boys from the United Arab Emirates (UAE) under a coaching camp organised by a private academy.         
	 Karachi: Pakistan all-rounder Sohail Tanvir Friday pulled out of a contract with Australian side Victoria after doctors advised him to rest an injured knee. The 25-year-old was due to play for the Bushrangers in the Australian T20 meet, but he has instead informed the Victoria of his unavailability, on medical advice.        
	 Calcutta: The BCCI has named Chinmoy Roy in the teaching faculty of the National Cricket Academy (NCA), Bangalore, for a three-day fitness trainers level O course. The course began in Nagpur on Friday.                                                                                                                                                      
